post_cb({"5291008": {"ViewCount": "366", "Body": "<pre><code>float minTime[7]={FLT_MAX};\n    for(int i=0;i&lt;7;i++)\n        cout &lt;&lt; \"Min: \" &lt;&lt; minTime[i] &lt;&lt; endl;\n</code></pre>\n<p>Why do I get in the following output :</p>\n<pre><code>Min: 3.40282e+038\nMin: 0\nMin: 0\nMin: 0\n...\n</code></pre>\n<p>Shoudln't all have the same value as the first one? As it is refered here:\n<a href=\"http://www.fredosaurus.com/notes-cpp/arrayptr/array-initialization.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">C++ Notes</a></p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "5291024", "Title": "c++ array initialization", "CreationDate": "2011-03-13T17:18:17.513", "Id": "5291008", "CommentCount": "1", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastActivityDate": "2011-03-13T17:53:27.857", "Score": "1", "OwnerUserId": "652564", "Tags": "<c++><arrays>", "AnswerCount": "3"}, "5291024": {"Id": "5291024", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_5291008_5291024_0\">Shoudln't all have the same value as the first one? </p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Nopes! When an array is partially initialized the non-initialized array elements are value initialized (<em>zero-initialized</em> in this case).</p>\n<p><strong>C++03 Section 8.5.1/7</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_5291008_5291024_1\">If there are fewer initializers  in  the  list  than  there  are  members  in  the  aggregate,  then  each  member  not explicitly initialized shall be <strong>value-initialized</strong> \n  (8.5).<br>\n  [Example:</br></p>\n<pre><code>struct S { int a; char* b; int c; };\nS ss = { 1, \"asdf\" };\n</code></pre>\n<p id=\"so_5291008_5291024_2\">initializes <code>ss.a</code> with  1, <code>ss.b</code> with \"asdf\",  and <code>ss.c</code> with  the  value  of  an  expression  of  the  form\n  int(), that is, 0.  ]</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "165520", "LastActivityDate": "2011-03-13T17:25:55.260", "Score": "3", "CreationDate": "2011-03-13T17:20:25.010", "ParentId": "5291008", "CommentCount": "3", "OwnerUserId": "165520", "LastEditDate": "2011-03-13T17:25:55.260"}, "5291043": {"Id": "5291043", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Your linked page says \"...the unspecified elements are set to zero.\"</p>\n<p>This is correct; as such, only the first element in your array was specified to be <code>FLT_MAX</code>, the rest are initialized to zero. If you want to set them all to the same value you can use a for-loop, or more succinctly:</p>\n<pre><code>std::fill_n(minTime, 7, FLT_MAX);\n</code></pre>\n<hr>\n<p>As a warning, C++ is a hard language. This means lots of people have lots of misinformation, and this is especially easy to find on the internet. You'd be better off learning from a <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/388242/the-definitive-c-book-guide-and-list\">book on our list</a>. (And yes, the ones <em>not</em> on our list are so because they too contain misinformation!)</p>\n</hr>", "LastEditorUserId": "-1", "LastActivityDate": "2011-03-13T17:22:16.980", "Score": "4", "CreationDate": "2011-03-13T17:22:16.980", "ParentId": "5291008", "CommentCount": "2", "OwnerUserId": "87234", "LastEditDate": "2017-05-23T12:15:28.880"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_5291008_5291024_1": {"length": 12, "quality": 0.8, "section_id": 3304}, "so_5291008_5291024_2": {"length": 9, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 3304}, "so_5291008_5291024_0": {"length": 5, "quality": 0.7142857142857143, "section_id": 6172}}, "n3337": {"so_5291008_5291024_1": {"length": 12, "quality": 0.8, "section_id": 3174}, "so_5291008_5291024_0": {"length": 5, "quality": 0.7142857142857143, "section_id": 5933}, "so_5291008_5291024_2": {"length": 9, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 3174}}, "n4659": {"so_5291008_5291024_1": {"length": 10, "quality": 0.6666666666666666, "section_id": 4070}, "so_5291008_5291024_0": {"length": 4, "quality": 0.5714285714285714, "section_id": 572}, "so_5291008_5291024_2": {"length": 9, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 4070}}}, "5291034": {"Id": "5291034", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>No, only first value is initialized with the supplied value, other values are value initialized as per standard.</p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "392315", "LastActivityDate": "2011-03-13T17:53:27.857", "Score": "1", "CreationDate": "2011-03-13T17:21:12.870", "ParentId": "5291008", "CommentCount": "1", "OwnerUserId": "392315", "LastEditDate": "2011-03-13T17:53:27.857"}});